default2. Direct payment of housing costs to claimantsdefault2.1 
defaultWe appreciate the principle of replicating the world of work and encouraging those i
defaultn receipt of benefits to manage their finances in similar fashion to those who are working. 
default&#xa0;default2.2 However we are aware that 
defaultt
defaulthe direct payment demonstration projects are already showing an increase in rent arrears, despite 
defaultorganisations 
defaultincreasing 
defaulttheir 
defaultstaff resources to manage the process. 
defaultThe fear is therefore that l
defaultandlords will not be able to replicate this level of intensive management across their entire stock, with a real concern that arrears levels will increase further.
default The risks are potentially
default greater within a supported housing environment as the incidence of v
defaultulnerable tenants
default will be greater and such tenants may be the 
defaultleast likely to be able to maintain rent payments to their landlord. The Local Support Services Framework sets out extensive 
defaultmeasures to assist those most vulnerable and needing support to cope, but introduces new bureaucracy and processes
default.
default&#xa0;
default2.3 
defaultWe believe that landlords, in consultation with their tenants, should be able to agree how rent is paid to them. Most supported housing
default providers will 
defaultwork to promote the independence of their tenants and will recognise when it is appropriate to have rent paid direct to them, bypassing the tenant, and when it makes sense for the tenant to take personal responsibility. 
default&#xa0;
default2.4 Should the cur
defaultrent commitment to direct payments remain then t
defaulthe ability for direct payments to revert back to the landlord at a two month trigger point is welcome and necessary; 
defaultas is the intention to allow potential reversion to be discussed after one month. B
defaultut for m
defaultany vulnerable tenants 
defaultthe uncertainty and anxiety caused during these initial weeks 
defaultcould be avoided entirely 
defaultif the landlord and the tenant could agree at the outset how best rent was to be paid.
