default3. Household benefit capdefault3.1 Allowing those living within
default supported accommodation to come within the total benefit cap, whilst ignoring 
defaultactual 
defaulthelp with housing costs when calculating the cap 
defaultfor anyone in exempt accommodation, is extremely complicated.  In practice, those living in exempt accommodation are ofte
defaultn disabled and by ignoring both their housing costs and disability benefits, the majority fall well 
defaultbelow 
defaultthe cap. 
defaultHowever the
default current definition of exempt accommodation remains far from clear
default.
default 
defaultT
defaulthis means that those living in supported accommodation which is not considered exempt 
defaultface having
default their total benefits capped
default; even though their circumstances may differ very little from those in exempt accommodation.
default&#xa0;
default3.2 We feel strongly that it is time 
defaultfor the definition of exempt accommodation to be clarified for providers, local authorities and tenants. W
defaulte also feel that w
defaulthatever the final definition, 
defaultthe cap would be greatly simplified by omitting all supported
default housing as this would ensure that those 
defaultof working age living in supported housing can receive the full support of the welfare system which they need.
