default4. defaultSocialdefault sector size criteriadefault4.1 Evidence of application of the social sector size criteria so far indicates that this is counter productive 
defaultand cannot achieve the stated aim of better use of housing stock. 
default4.2 
defaultWe are 
defaultparticularly concerned that the criteria penalise 
defaultboth 
defaultdisabled couples and single claimants who require an additional bedroom for health reasons – whether this be a medical need
default to sleep separately, or to accommodate essential medical equipment. 
defaultT
defaulthis is often likely to be the case in supported housing
default as those with such medical needs also have wider support needs
default; and as much supported housing is not currently considered to be ex
defaultempt
default from the size criteria
default, vulnerable disabled people are disadvantaged. Indeed, many 
defaultmay 
defaultnot need high levels of other support
default, but
default 
defaultdo
default actually need the extra bedroom
default as a form of support to maintain their independence and well being.
default&#xa0;
default4.3 
defaultSince 2006 
defaultDepartment of Health funding for new extra care developments has specified that properties should have 3 habitable rooms. This is still the case for Home and Communities Agency funding. New schemes are funded and developed on this bas
defaultis
default. The Department for
default Work and Pension will now potentially say that this is too large for the household's needs and the resident will see a reduction in their housing benefit entitlement due to the size criteria restrictions
default.
default&#xa0;
default4.4 
defaultFor many disabled people in the social sector
default, downsizing therefore will not be an option. However those who cannot afford to retain the spare bedroom may be forced to look to alternative accommodation in the private sector which may not 
defaultultimately be cheaper, and which will not reduce the benefits b
defaultill. 
defaultThe lack of suitable alternative accommodation is a major concern. The availability of one bedroom properties puts severe restrictions and limitation on the ability for people to downsize. People are often stuck in a situation where there housing bene
defaultfit entitlement is restricted as the property is deemed too large for their needs but there is no smaller accommodation available.
default&#xa0;
default4.
default5
default 
defaultWe are concerned about adults with disabilities and are unsure as to why disabled children are not expected to have to s
defaulthare a bedroom whereas a recent 
defaultH
defaultigh 
defaultC
defaultourt judgement has said that disabled adults are expected to share a bedroom. Often with older people, even if they wanted to share a bedroom, this is not always practical a
defaults a result of health problems. We realise tha
defaultt this
default recent judicial review does not support our contention that those with a proven disability and medical need for an extra bedroom should be able to receive help with the cost of this
default. However we remain convinced
default that it is still appropriate 
defaultthat the 
defaultimplications and impact upon vulnerable disabled claimants should be reconsidered
default as part of this review
