default5. defaultLocaliseddefault council tax supportdefault5.1 
defaultWe all 
defaultwork across a large number of local authorit
defaulties
default, and 
defaultare 
defaultun
defaultaware of any which have not adhered to the 
defaultguidance that vulnerable claimants should not receive less council tax support than they did previously under Council Tax Benefit.
default This is welcome; however we fear that as local authority budgets become more restricted, the lack of a national system will i
defaultncreasingly lead to local variation and the ‘postcode lottery’ principle.
default&#xa0;
default5.2 Without a national demand led system, local circumstances and budgetary pressures will inevitably mean that disabled people and those in supported accommodation will eventually 
defaultfind that the level of help they can expect with council tax varies between areas, irrespective of their personal circumstances. This will undermine the support that they receive elsewhere, and the safety net will become increasingly disjointed and fragmen
defaultted.
default6. Tdefaultreatment of housing costs within Universal Creditdefault6.1
default 
defaultOur 
defaultmajor concerns concentrate on the following areas –
default service charge provisions; benefit overlaps when moving home; temporary absence provisions; waiting periods; and notification of housing cost awards.
default&#xa0;
default6.2
default defaultService charge provisions are restricted in comparison to Housing Benefit.default 
defaultThe principles appear to assume that the majority of working age claimants occupy straightforward property with very little in the way of services apart from fairly standard items such as refuse collection, car parking, gardening. The new service charge pr
defaultovisions do not sufficiently reflect the complexity of 
defaultsupported housing and the additional facilities this may provide.
defaultWe hope that the provisions for window cleaning costs are not replicated in any service charge provision for older people, as we consid
defaulter that it is unhelpful for anyone living in sheltered housing to be expected to 
defaultclean
default windows at any level.
default&#xa0;
default6.3
default defaultLack of any provision for overlap of benefit when moving home.default defaultIt is extremely difficult for those on the lowest incomes to pay for a notice period as well as the rent for a new property when moving home. The majority of disabled people and those needing supported housing do not move on a whim, but because they need m
defaultore suitable accommodation. Without help with housing costs, many will be unable to accept the 
defaultaccommodation they badly need and local strategies to meet specific housing need will not be met.
default&#xa0;
defaultThis lack of provision to meet housing costs for a notice peri
defaultod is also likely to affect those wishing to downsize to avoid social sector size criteria penalties. We do not believe that discretionary housing payment funding will remain sufficient to cover this, and that these provisions act as a deterrent to the aim
default of achieving better use of housing stock nationally.
default&#xa0;default6.4 
defaultA standard six month provision for absence from home.default defaultA blanket provision for absence from home for any reason provides administrative simplicity, but lacks fairness
default. Replacing the present 13 week
default absence rule within Housing Benefit with six months for Universal Credit, provides an over generous opportunity for those who are not genuinely occupying the property as their home; whilst simultaneously penalising the sick and disabled who may need to sp
defaultend an extended time in hospital or nursing care. Such claimants will be forced into a choice between rent arrears or not receiving the nursing care and support they need. Ultimately for some this will lead to increased dependence upon state resources at a
default far higher cost.
default6.5
default Tdefaulthe decision to apply the waiting period to the whole Universal Credit award.   defaultWe 
defaultunderstand that this will only apply to claimants who are expected to work and have full work-related requirements; but it is unclear how this might a
defaultffect vulnerable and disabled claimants. There are many with disabilities 
defaultthat
default are expected and able to work, and who wish to do so
default; however they may find themselves placed in the full work requirement group. Many will already find that they receive less 
defaulthelp 
defaultthrough premiums within Universal Credit, and having to wait an extra 7 days before receiving any housing costs will place an additional obstacle in their way.
default&#xa0;
defaultOverall we consider that a total waiting period of up to 38 days before a first payment is
default made will penalise those on the lowest incomes who are most in need of help at the start of their claim. This does not accurately reflect the world of work for many low paid workers who are not usually expected to work their first week without getting pai
defaultd at all; and who are often paid weekly rather than salaried monthly. No one on a salary is expected to wait that long for their first payment. 
default&#xa0;
defaultAn increase in those on very low incomes who are desperately short of money at the start of their claim, will 
defaultlead to an increase in requests for help via local welfare provision – at a time when local schemes are already providing less assistance due to restricted funding. 
defaultScarce resources will therefore be further pressured by the poorest having nowhere else to 
defaultturn for assistance during the extended waiting period. 
default&#xa0;
defaultWe 
defaultstrongly 
defaultfeel that the precise detail of how this provision will apply to vulnerable and disabled people 
defaulttherefore 
defaultneeds further careful consideration. 
default&#xa0;
default6.6
default&#xa0; 
defaultNotification of amount of housing costs. defaultAlthough Universal Credit is meant to replicate a wage by being paid as a single payment, we see no purpose in not clearly identifying actual amounts towards housing costs within the award. We hope that everyone will receive notification of awards which c
defaultlearly show how much help is being provided towards housing costs
default, as this will assist in supporting claimants towards managing their own payments.
default&#xa0;
default7. Implications of future changes for older peopledefault7.1 
defaultA
defaultll three 
defaultproviders 
defaultappreciate that how support for 
defaulthousing costs is delivered for older people is outside the scope of this inquiry; but we do not want to miss the opportunity to comment on this. We urge that very careful consideration is given to how help towards housing costs within Pension Credit is det
defaultermined, and how this aligns with Universal Credit provisions.
default7.2 We consider that the issues of eligible service charges, overlap of benefit for two homes, and period of absence from home for hospital or respite care, would pose significant problems for 
defaultolder people should these provisions be replicated within Pension Credit. There would be consequences for older people being able to downsize from family homes
default, as well as the inability to move to smaller suitable supported accommodation. This would lead t
defaulto many being unable to remain living 
defaultindependently for longer, with consequent increased social care costs. We remain convinced that such consequences would be unintended and counter productive.
default&#xa0;
default7.3 In conclusion, w
defaulte are aware that the DWP are currently r
defaulteviewing the definition of 'exempt accommodation' status for housing benefit purposes. The current definition states that the landlord or a person acting on their behalf also provides the claimant with care, support or supervision. The government is pushin
defaultg the personalisation agenda, whereby people are encouraged to receive direct payments rather than care packages organised by Social Services. With personalisation, the landlord is less like to be involved in the provision of care as individuals will take 
defaultresponsibility for organising their own care.
default&#xa0;
defaultIt is very important 
defaultfor 
defaultthe new definition of exempt accommodation that this is factored in, particularly in relation to extra care properties. 
